    <div class="card-info" id="cardInfo">
    <h2>Martinus Willem Beijerinck</h2>
    <p><strong>Lifetime:</strong> 1851â€“1931</p>
    <p><strong>Title:</strong> Pioneer of General Microbiology</p>
    <p><strong>Achievements:</strong> Beijerinck's work with tobacco mosaic disease (TMD) was groundbreaking. Scientists knew the disease was contagious but couldn't find a bacterial cause. Beijerinck used filters that are good enough to trap bacteria, yet sap from diseased plants, after being filtered, could still infect healthy plants. This led him to conclude that the infectious agent was smaller than bacteria, a new type of pathogen he named "virus" (Latin for "poison").</p>
    <p><strong>Legacy:</strong> Beijerinck's discovery was a paradigm shift in understanding disease. It revealed a previously unknown world of submicroscopic pathogens that could not be cultured using traditional bacteriological methods. This had profound implications for human health, paving the way for the study and eventual control of viral diseases like influenza, polio, and measles. His work also impacted agriculture by studying plant viruses, which later became essential to biotechnology and genetic engineering advancements.</p>
</div>


    <script>
        const card = document.getElementById('gameCard');
        const cardInfo = document.getElementById('cardInfo');

        card.addEventListener('click', () => {
            card.classList.toggle('is-flipped');
            cardInfo.classList.toggle('visible');
        });
    </script>

